explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER — The macro/inline expands to code that may log, abort, or return on a NULL filestats pointer. Whether it can return or otherwise change control flow determines if subsequent operations (memset, calls) are reachable and therefore whether those operations could be dead code.

memset — Performs the write that might be considered dead (zeroing *filestats). You need its exact semantics and the bytes written to determine whether removing the memset would change observable program behaviour (e.g. caller-visible contents on error paths).

os_fstat_t — The type of *filestats. Its size and fields determine whether zeroing it is meaningful (initialization vs assignment) and whether later code always overwrites those fields (making the memset potentially dead).

sizeof(*filestats) — The argument passed to memset. The exact size/number of bytes cleared affects whether memset is redundant relative to what OS_FileStat_Impl writes or what callers inspect.

OS_TranslatePath — Its return semantics and side effects (does it modify filestats, does it always fail/succeed under some inputs, does it have observable side effects) determine whether the branch that calls OS_FileStat_Impl is taken and whether the memset remains observable on error paths.

OS_FileStat_Impl — Its behaviour and which fields of filestats it writes are critical: if it always fully populates filestats on success and the memset only matters on failure, or if it partially populates filestats, the memset may or may not be dead.

OS_SUCCESS — The value tested after OS_TranslatePath; understanding what constitutes success determines branch execution and therefore whether earlier operations (memset) affect behaviour.

OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN — Size of local_path buffer. Needed to reason about whether OS_TranslatePath can write the buffer, whether any truncation/overflow changes behaviour, and whether local_path storage has any side effects that could make earlier operations necessary.

OS_printf — Often used by pointer-check macros to log errors; if OS_CHECK_POINTER calls OS_printf, that produces observable behaviour (logging) so its presence/absence affects whether other operations are dead.

OS_INVALID_POINTER (or the actual return code used by OS_CHECK_POINTER) — If OS_CHECK_POINTER returns a specific error code on NULL, that return value is observable to callers. Knowing this code is necessary to assess whether subsequent operations executed in the non-NULL case are required for correct behaviour.

Note: the above symbols (macros, types, prototypes and constants) are the minimal set required to decide if the memset or other operations in OS_stat could be removed without changing observable behaviour (the definition of dead code under MISRA).
